{"title_page": "Luigi Ghirri", "text_new": "'''Luigi Ghirri''' (5 January 1943 \u2013 14 February 1992) was an Italian [[artist]] and [[photographer]]<ref name=\"nytimes-cole\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/arts/07iht-venice07.html | date = 28 June 2016 | accessdate = 18 August 2017| first = Teju | last = Cole | authorlink = Teju Cole | work = [[The New York Times Magazine]] | title = Luigi Ghirri\u2019s Brilliant Photographic Puzzles}}</ref><ref name=\"frieze\">{{cite journal | url = http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/all-other-images | date = 1 November 2011 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Christy | last = Lange | work = [[frieze (magazine)|frieze]] | issue = 143 | title = All Other Images: The legacy of the late Italian photographer Luigi Ghirri}}</ref> who gained a far-reaching reputation as a pioneer and master of contemporary photography, with particular reference to its relationship between fiction and reality.<ref name=\"time-ladd\">{{cite news | url = http://time.com/69090/luigi-ghirris-kodachromes-revisited/ | date = 6 May 2013 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Jeffrey | last = Ladd | magazine = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | title = Luigi Ghirri's Kodachromes Revisited}}</ref>\n\nGhirri has been the subject of numerous books. His works are held by various museums around the world and have been exhibited in the 2011 [[Venice Biennale]]<ref name=\"nytimes-morris\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/arts/07iht-venice07.html | date = 6 June 2011 | accessdate = 18 August 2017| first = Roderick | last = Conway Morris | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | title = Venice Biennale Thrives Despite Tough Economic Times}}</ref> and at [[MAXXI]] in Rome.<ref name=\"icp\">{{cite web | url = https://icplibrary.wordpress.com/2014/07/14/luigi-ghirri-the-absolute-fascination-of-the-image/ | date = 14 July 2014 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | publisher = [[International Center of Photography]] | work = International Center of Photography Library  | first = Emiliano | last = Cavicchi | title = Luigi Ghirri, the Absolute Fascination of the Image}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nGhirri was born in [[Scandiano]]<ref name=\"dazed-christiansen\">{{cite web | url = http://www.dazeddigital.com/photography/article/16236/1/luigi-ghirri | date = 30 May 2013 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Hanne | last = Christiansen | publisher = [[Dazed]] | title = Luigi Ghirri: Saluting the photographer who discovered today's soft, elegant nostalgia back in 70s Italy}}</ref><ref name=\"independent-keates\">{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/visual-arts-the-italy-where-less-is-more-1111828.html | date = 9 August 1999 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Jonathan | last = Keates | newspaper = [[The Independent]] | location = London | title = Visual Arts: The Italy where less is more}}</ref> near [[Reggio Emilia]], Italy, on 5 January 1943.\n\nHe started his career in the 1970s. Influenced by conceptual art, he created his first two series, ''Atlante'' (1973) and ''Kodachrome'' (1978),<ref name=\"time-ladd\" /><ref name=\"dazed-christiansen\" /> where his cropped images of the landscape were presented with a deadpan, often ironic wit and a continuous anthropological engagement with his surroundings.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The compositions and hues of his photographs suggested subtle emotional tones and a meticulously rich way of viewing the world, as well as the role of images within it.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nGhirri's work quickly attracted international attention. In 1975 [[Time-Life]] included him in its list of the \"Discoveries\" of its annual Photography Year publication, and he showed at the ''Photography as Art, Art as Photography'' exhibition in Kassel. In 1982 he was invited to the [[photokina 1982|photokina]] in Cologne, where he was acclaimed as one of the twenty most significant photographers of the 20th century for his series ''Topographie-Iconographie''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} In 1989 he made a series shot in the studio of painter [[Giorgio Morandi]].\n\nHe died of a heart attack at the age of 49<ref name=\"independent-keates\" /> in Roncocesi, [[Province of Reggio Emilia]], Italy on 14 February 1992.\n\n==Publications==\n*''Kodachrome.'' Self-published / Punto e Virgola, 1978.\n**London: [[Mack (publishing)|Mack]], 2012. {{ISBN|9781907946240}}. With an essay by Francesco Zanot in Italian, English, French and German; and translations of the original texts in French and German.\n*''Italian Landscape/Paesaggio Italiano'' (no.11 in the book series ''Lotus Documents'' directed by Pierluigi Nicolin), Hamburg: Gingko Press, 1989; Comprises 83 colour plates and 14 essays and interviews by Ghirri and various contributors. 128pp. \n*''Il Profilo Delle Nuvole. Immagini di un Paesaggio Italiano.'' Milan: [[Feltrinelli (publisher)|Feltrinelli]], 1996.\n*''Atlante.'' Charta, 2000. {{ISBN|978-8881582648}}.\n*''Niente di antico sotto il sole.'' Torino: SEI, 1997; ''The Complete Essays.'' London: Mack, 2016. {{ISBN|9781910164143}}.\n*''Luigi Ghirri.'' Tokyo: Taka Ishii, 2017. Text in English and Japanese.\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Solo exhibitions===\n* Luigi Ghirri, curated by Manfred Willmann, Fotogalerie im Forum Stadtpark, Graz, Austria, 31 March \u2013 27 April 1976.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*''Paesaggio Italiano'' (Italian Landscape), organised by the Assessorato alla Cultura del Comune di Reggio Emilia, [[Reggio Emilia]], Italy, 1 July - 20 August 1989.<ref>''Italian Landscape'', Gingko Press, 1989</ref>\n*''It\u2019s Beautiful Here, Isn\u2019t It\u2026,'' [[Aperture Foundation]], New York City, 2008\u20132009<ref>{{cite web | url = http://aperture.org/exhibition/luigi-ghirri-beautiful-isnt/ | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | publisher = [[Aperture Foundation]] | title =  Luigi Ghirri: It\u2019s Beautiful Here, Isn\u2019t It\u2026: November 07, 2008 - January 02, 2009}}</ref>\n*''Kodachrome,'' [[Matthew Marks Gallery]], New York City, 2013.<ref name=\"nytimes-rosenberg\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/29/arts/design/luigi-ghirri-kodachrome.html | date = 28 March 2013 | accessdate = 18 August 2017| first = Matthew | last = Rosenberg | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | title = Luigi Ghirri: \u2018Kodachrome\u2019}}</ref>\n*''Luigi Ghirri \u2018Thinking Images\u2019 Icons, Landscapes, Architectures,'' [[MAXXI]], Rome, 2013; Brazil; [[Reggio Emilia]], Italy, 2014. A retrospective, curated by Francesca Fabiani, Laura Gasparini, and Giuliano Sergio.<ref name=\"icp\" />\n*''Cartes et Territoires (The Map and the Territory),'' [[Museum Folkwang]], Essen, 4 May \u2013 22 July 2018; [[Museo Reina Sof\u00eda]], Madrid, 26 September 2018 \u2013 7 January 2019; [[Galerie nationale du Jeu de Paume|Jeu de paume]], Paris, 12 February \u2013 2 June 2019. Curated by [[James Lingwood]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Luigi Ghirri: The Map and the Territory |url=https://www.museoreinasofia.es/en/exhibitions/luigi-ghirri-map-and-territory |website=Museo Reina Sof\u00eda |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=14 February 2019|title=Luigi Ghirri: Cartes et territoires|url=http://www.jeudepaume.org/index.php?page=article&idArt=3242|website=Le Jeu de Paume}}</ref>\n\n===Group exhibitions===\n*[[Photokina 1982|Photokina]], Cologne, Germany, 1982{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*''Luigi Ghirri/[[Aldo Rossi]]: Things Which Are Only Themselves'', [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], Montreal, Canada, 1996<ref>{{cite web |title=Luigi Ghirri/Aldo Rossi: Things Which Are Only Themselves |url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/2711/luigi-ghirrialdo-rossi-things-which-are-only-themselves |website=[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n*''ILLUMInations,'' [[Venice Biennale]], Venice, Italy, 2011. Group exhibition, curated by [[Bice Curiger]].<ref name=\"nytimes-morris\" />\n*''Photography as Art, Art as Photography,'' Kassel, 1975{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\n==Collections==\nGhirri's work is held in the following permanent collections:\n*[[Stedelijk Museum]], Amsterdam<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stedelijk.nl/en/collectie/maker/23213-luigi-ghirri|title=Luigi Ghirri|website=Stedelijk.nl|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Museo di fotografia contemporanea|it}}, Milan, Italy<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mufoco.org/en/collections/viaggio-in-italia-fund/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222044318/https://www.mufoco.org/en/collections/viaggio-in-italia-fund/ |archive-date=2 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]], Paris<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.bnf.fr/en/11904803/luigi_ghirri/|title=Luigi Ghirri (1943-1992)|website=Data.bnf.fr|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], Montreal, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Luigi Ghirri, Photographs |url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search?page=0&query=luigi+ghirri&_=1586288919291&filters=%7B%22forms_collection_library_bookstore%22%3A%5B%22photographs%22%5D%7D |website=[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]], TX<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfah.org/art/search?sort=accession,asc&nationality=Italian&artist=Luigi+Ghirri|title=Search the Collection - The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|website=Mfah.org|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], New York City<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/39882|title=Luigi Ghirri - MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Piero Gemelli]]\n*[[Conceptualism]]\n*[[Franco Fontana]]\n*[[Gianni Celati]]\n*[[Paul Strand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghirri, Luigi}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian photographers]]\n[[Category:Italian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Reggio Emilia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Luigi Ghirri''' (5 January 1943 \u2013 14 February 1992) was an Italian [[artist]] and [[photographer]]<ref name=\"nytimes-cole\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/arts/07iht-venice07.html | date = 28 June 2016 | accessdate = 18 August 2017| first = Teju | last = Cole | authorlink = Teju Cole | work = [[The New York Times Magazine]] | title = Luigi Ghirri\u2019s Brilliant Photographic Puzzles}}</ref><ref name=\"frieze\">{{cite journal | url = http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/all-other-images | date = 1 November 2011 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Christy | last = Lange | work = [[frieze (magazine)|frieze]] | issue = 143 | title = All Other Images: The legacy of the late Italian photographer Luigi Ghirri}}</ref> who gained a far-reaching reputation as a pioneer and master of contemporary photography, with particular reference to its relationship between fiction and reality.<ref name=\"time-ladd\">{{cite news | url = http://time.com/69090/luigi-ghirris-kodachromes-revisited/ | date = 6 May 2013 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Jeffrey | last = Ladd | magazine = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | title = Luigi Ghirri's Kodachromes Revisited}}</ref>\n\nGhirri has been the subject of numerous books. His works are held by various museums around the world and have been exhibited in the 2011 [[Venice Biennale]]<ref name=\"nytimes-morris\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/07/arts/07iht-venice07.html | date = 6 June 2011 | accessdate = 18 August 2017| first = Roderick | last = Conway Morris | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | title = Venice Biennale Thrives Despite Tough Economic Times}}</ref> and at [[MAXXI]] in Rome.<ref name=\"icp\">{{cite web | url = https://icplibrary.wordpress.com/2014/07/14/luigi-ghirri-the-absolute-fascination-of-the-image/ | date = 14 July 2014 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | publisher = [[International Center of Photography]] | work = International Center of Photography Library  | first = Emiliano | last = Cavicchi | title = Luigi Ghirri, the Absolute Fascination of the Image}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nGhirri was born in [[Scandiano]]<ref name=\"dazed-christiansen\">{{cite web | url = http://www.dazeddigital.com/photography/article/16236/1/luigi-ghirri | date = 30 May 2013 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Hanne | last = Christiansen | publisher = [[Dazed]] | title = Luigi Ghirri: Saluting the photographer who discovered today's soft, elegant nostalgia back in 70s Italy}}</ref><ref name=\"independent-keates\">{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/visual-arts-the-italy-where-less-is-more-1111828.html | date = 9 August 1999 | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | first = Jonathan | last = Keates | newspaper = [[The Independent]] | location = London | title = Visual Arts: The Italy where less is more}}</ref> near [[Reggio Emilia]], Italy, on 5 January 1943.\n\nHe started his career in the 1970s. Influenced by conceptual art, he created his first two series, ''Atlante'' (1973) and ''Kodachrome'' (1978),<ref name=\"time-ladd\" /><ref name=\"dazed-christiansen\" /> where his cropped images of the landscape were presented with a deadpan, often ironic wit and a continuous anthropological engagement with his surroundings.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The compositions and hues of his photographs suggested subtle emotional tones and a meticulously rich way of viewing the world, as well as the role of images within it.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nGhirri's work quickly attracted international attention. In 1975 [[Time-Life]] included him in its list of the \"Discoveries\" of its annual Photography Year publication, and he showed at the ''Photography as Art, Art as Photography'' exhibition in Kassel. In 1982 he was invited to the [[photokina 1982|photokina]] in Cologne, where he was acclaimed as one of the twenty most significant photographers of the 20th century for his series ''Topographie-Iconographie''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} In 1989 he made a series shot in the studio of painter [[Giorgio Morandi]].\n\nHe died of a heart attack at the age of 49<ref name=\"independent-keates\" /> in Roncocesi, [[Province of Reggio Emilia]], Italy on 14 February 1992.\n\n==Publications==\n*''Kodachrome.'' Self-published / Punto e Virgola, 1978.\n**London: [[Mack (publishing)|Mack]], 2012. {{ISBN|9781907946240}}. With an essay by Francesco Zanot in Italian, English, French and German; and translations of the original texts in French and German.\n*''Italian Landscape/Paesaggio Italiano'' (no.11 in the book series ''Lotus Documents'' directed by Pierluigi Nicolin), Hamburg: Gingko Press, 1989; Comprises 83 colour plates and 14 essays and interviews by Ghirri and various contributors. 128pp. \n*''Il Profilo Delle Nuvole. Immagini di un Paesaggio Italiano.'' Milan: [[Feltrinelli (publisher)|Feltrinelli]], 1996.\n*''Atlante.'' Charta, 2000. {{ISBN|978-8881582648}}.\n*''Niente di antico sotto il sole.'' Torino: SEI, 1997; ''The Complete Essays.'' London: Mack, 2016. {{ISBN|9781910164143}}.\n*''Luigi Ghirri.'' Tokyo: Taka Ishii, 2017. Text in English and Japanese.\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Solo exhibitions===\n* Luigi Ghirri, curated by Manfred Willmann, Fotogalerie im Forum Stadtpark, Graz, Austria, 31 March \u2013 27 April 1976.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*''Paesaggio Italiano'' (Italian Landscape), organised by the Assessorato alla Cultura del Comune di Reggio Emilia, [[Reggio Emilia]], Italy, 1 July - 20 August 1989.<ref>''Italian Landscape'', Gingko Press, 1989</ref>\n*''It\u2019s Beautiful Here, Isn\u2019t It\u2026,'' [[Aperture Foundation]], New York City, 2008\u20132009<ref>{{cite web | url = http://aperture.org/exhibition/luigi-ghirri-beautiful-isnt/ | accessdate = 18 August 2017 | publisher = [[Aperture Foundation]] | title =  Luigi Ghirri: It\u2019s Beautiful Here, Isn\u2019t It\u2026: November 07, 2008 - January 02, 2009}}</ref>\n*''Kodachrome,'' [[Matthew Marks Gallery]], New York City, 2013.<ref name=\"nytimes-rosenberg\">{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/29/arts/design/luigi-ghirri-kodachrome.html | date = 28 March 2013 | accessdate = 18 August 2017| first = Matthew | last = Rosenberg | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | title = Luigi Ghirri: \u2018Kodachrome\u2019}}</ref>\n*''Luigi Ghirri \u2018Thinking Images\u2019 Icons, Landscapes, Architectures,'' [[MAXXI]], Rome, 2013; Brazil; [[Reggio Emilia]], Italy, 2014. A retrospective, curated by Francesca Fabiani, Laura Gasparini, and Giuliano Sergio.<ref name=\"icp\" />\n*''Cartes et Territoires (The Map and the Territory),'' [[Jeu de paume]], Paris, February\u2013June 2019. Curated by [[James Lingwood]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-02-14|title=Luigi Ghirri|url=http://www.jeudepaume.org/index.php?page=article&idArt=3242|website=Le Jeu de Paume}}</ref>\n\n===Group exhibitions===\n*''Photography as Art, Art as Photography,'' Kassel, 1975{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*[[Photokina 1982|Photokina]], Cologne, Germany, 1982{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n*''ILLUMInations,'' [[Venice Biennale]], Venice, Italy, 2011. Group exhibition, curated by [[Bice Curiger]].<ref name=\"nytimes-morris\" />\n\n==Collections==\nGhirri's work is held in the following permanent collections:\n*[[Stedelijk Museum]], Amsterdam<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stedelijk.nl/en/collectie/maker/23213-luigi-ghirri|title=Luigi Ghirri|website=Stedelijk.nl|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Museo di fotografia contemporanea|it}}, Milan, Italy<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mufoco.org/en/collections/viaggio-in-italia-fund/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222044318/https://www.mufoco.org/en/collections/viaggio-in-italia-fund/ |archive-date=2018-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]], Paris<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.bnf.fr/en/11904803/luigi_ghirri/|title=Luigi Ghirri (1943-1992)|website=Data.bnf.fr|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], Montreal, Canada<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/8296 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222165026/https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/8296 |archive-date=2018-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]], TX<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mfah.org/art/search?sort=accession,asc&nationality=Italian&artist=Luigi+Ghirri|title=Search the Collection - The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|website=Mfah.org|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], New York City<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/39882|title=Luigi Ghirri - MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Piero Gemelli]]\n*[[Conceptualism]]\n*[[Franco Fontana]]\n*[[Gianni Celati]]\n*[[Paul Strand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghirri, Luigi}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian photographers]]\n[[Category:Italian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Reggio Emilia]]\n", "name_user": "Thomas Browne", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated link; added internal links; fixed internal link to Jeu de paume gallery; added Luigi Ghirri/Aldo Rossi exhibition; updated The Map and the Territory entry", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luigi_Ghirri"}
